    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "540ba15a2effdce7",
      "text": "Depending on the profession, they may work for three to four days a week in the company and then spend one or two days at a [[vocational school]] (''Berufsschule''). This is usually the case for trade and craftspeople. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "45d4f6e53447cf42",
      "text": "For other professions, usually which require more theoretical learning, the working and school times take place blockwise e.g., in a 12–18 weeks interval. These ''Berufsschulen'' have been part of the education system since the 19th century."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d29d0e72-76b3-4e4a-babf-97bdbd9b07f2",
      "text": "In 2001, two-thirds of young people aged under 22 began an apprenticeship, and 78% of them completed it, meaning that approximately 51% of all young people under 22 have completed an apprenticeship. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9a49f37ede5c892d",
      "text": "One in three companies offered apprenticeships in 2003, in 2004 the government signed a pledge with [[industrial union]]s that all companies except very small ones must take on apprentices."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ee8dae95-6be4-4f48-8f40-f65a58915baf",
      "text": "The latent decrease of the German population due to low [[birth rate]]s is now causing a lack of young people available to start an apprenticeship."
    },
