      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3680d13d-1883-4fc9-b12c-45518f37cb36",
      "text": "# Apprenticeship after general education"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ab0c1718-0f2c-4597-ba5c-1e3abde6f846",
      "text": "After graduation from school at the age of fifteen to nineteen (depending on type of school), students start an apprenticeship in their chosen professions. [[Realschule]] and Gymnasium ([[Gymnasium (Germany)]]) graduates usually have better chances for being accepted as an apprentice for sophisticated craft professions or apprenticeships in white-collar jobs in finance or administration. "
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "b6f48e58-7777-405a-be6d-1bc09d22a8f5",
      "text": "<div style='padding: 12px; background:#eee; width:96%; align=centered;'>\n<a href='https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-G0925-0036-001,_Chemiefaserwerk_Guben,_Meister_der_Zentralwerkstatt.jpg' target='_blank'>\n<img style='display:block; margin:auto; width:100%;'\nsrc='https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/64/Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-G0925-0036-001%2C_Chemiefaserwerk_Guben%2C_Meister_der_Zentralwerkstatt.jpg'>\n</a>\n\n<p class=caption>\nA master discusses a vacuum compressor with his apprentice (front left) and several other craftsmen\n[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-G0925-0036-001,_Chemiefaserwerk_Guben,_Meister_der_Zentralwerkstatt.jpg - wikimedia]\n</p></div>"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7d2b984eb9ac43cc",
      "text": "An apprenticeship takes between 2.5 and 3.5 years. Originally, at the beginning of the 20th century, less than 1% of German students attended the Gymnasium (the 8-9 year university-preparatory school) to obtain the Abitur graduation which was the only way to university back then. In the 1950's still only 5% of German youngsters entered university and in 1960 only 6% did. "
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "49e9da2a-289e-4104-ab45-43946bb67ac0",
      "text": "<div style='padding: 12px; background:#eee; width:96%; align=centered;'>\n<a href='https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Gesellen1.jpg' target='_blank'>\n<img style='display:block; margin:auto; width:100%;'\nsrc='https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/be/Gesellen1.jpg'>\n</a>\n\n<p class=caption>\nGerman journeymen during [[journeyman years]] in traditional costume\n[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Gesellen1.jpg - wikimedia]\n</p></div>"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b8cc91553ca0ce1c",
      "text": "Due to the risen social wealth and the increased demand for academic professionals in Germany, about 24% of the youngsters entered college/university in 2000. Of those, who did not enter university many started an apprenticeship. The apprenticeships usually end a person's education by age 18-20, but also older apprentices are accepted by the employers under certain conditions. This is frequently the case for immigrants from countries without a compatible professional training system."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d795032e-c91a-4b8a-a03a-8d451f5d6b31",
      "text": "# History"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "07a27fb5-499e-407d-b938-558dc776b877",
      "text": "In 1969, a law (the ''Berufsbildungsgesetz'') was passed which regulated and unified the vocational training system and codified the shared responsibility of the state, the unions, associations and the chambers of trade and industry. The dual system was successful in both parts of the divided Germany. In the GDR ([[German Democratic Republic]]), three-quarters of the working population had completed apprenticeships."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4b9946be-9a0d-4c2d-9cdf-10eba6b5117f",
      "text": "# Business and administrative professions"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "eef11b9f-4a98-416f-ae6c-bf838c042711",
      "text": "The precise skills and theory taught on German apprenticeships are strictly regulated. The employer is responsible for the entire education programme coordinated by the German [[chamber of commerce]]. Apprentices obtain a special apprenticeship contract until the end of the education programme. During the programme it is not allowed to assign the apprentice to regular employment and he is well protected from abrupt dismissal until the programme ends. The defined content and skill set of the apprentice profession must be fully provided and taught by the employer. The time taken is also regulated. Each profession takes a different time, usually between 24 and 36 months."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "44c82e83-a9a3-4a1d-b703-ba35c52dcb1d",
      "text": "Thus, everyone who had completed an apprenticeship e.g., as an industrial manager (''Industriekaufmann'') has learned the same skills and has attended the same courses in [[procurement]] and stocking up, controlling ([[control (management)]]), staffing ([[Human resources]]), [[accounting]] procedures, [[production planning]], [[terms of trade]] and transport [[logistics]] and various other subjects."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3766f48b-e72c-4561-87f7-4d02eb9782ca",
      "text": "Someone who has not taken this apprenticeship or did not pass the final examinations at the chamber of industry and commerce is not allowed to call himself an ''Industriekaufmann''. Most job titles are legally standardized and restricted. An employment in such function in any company would require this completed degree."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "61185f6d-9e28-4be7-a4ea-202f50ae957c",
      "text": "# Trade and craft professions"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "54e7ce62-ecf8-4980-896a-da11c384e6cd",
      "text": "The rules and laws for the trade and craftwork apprentices such as [[mechanic]]s, bakers ([[bakery]]), [[joiner]]s, etc. are as strict as and even broader than for the business professions. The involved procedures, titles and traditions still strongly reflect the [[medieval]] origin of the system. Here, the average duration is about 36 months, some specialized crafts even take up to 42 months."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f1067d3c-607e-4ae8-881e-80452e88936a",
      "text": "After completion of the dual education, e.g., a baker is allowed to call himself a bakery [[journeyman]] (''Bäckergeselle''). After the apprenticeship the journeyman can enter the master's school (''Meisterschule'') and continue his education at evening courses for 3–4 years or full-time for about one year. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0907553d519fcde7",
      "text": "The graduation from the master's school leads to the title of a [[master craftsman]] (''Meister'') of his profession, so e.g., a bakery master is entitled as ''Bäckermeister''. A master is officially entered in the local trade register, the craftspeople's roll (''Handwerksrolle''). A master craftsman is allowed to employ and to train new apprentices. In some mostly safety-related professions, e.g., that of [[electrician]]s only a master is allowed to found his own company."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "9bd24b0f-5b08-454a-94a4-c473f88c04ac",
      "text": "# License for educating apprentices"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8d189b63-1603-4c82-a294-836cda2ea47f",
      "text": "To employ and to educate apprentices requires a specific license. The AdA - ''Ausbildung der Ausbilder'' - \"Education of the Educators\" license needs to be acquired by a training at the chamber of industry and commerce."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e4a34076-42ef-4b8e-8e0d-5abf869ef6e7",
      "text": "The masters complete this license course within their own master's coursework. The training and examination of new masters is only possible for masters who have been working several years in their profession and who have been accepted by the chambers as a trainer and examiner."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2bf7e4e5-07c8-42d4-8073-98902ed75b4d",
      "text": "Academic professionals, e.g., [[engineer]]s, seeking this license need to complete the AdA during or after their university studies, usually by a one-year evening course."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cd4e9357-79f1-4095-a551-2d767c592087",
      "text": "The holder of the license is only allowed to train apprentices within his own field of expertise. For example, a [[mechanical engineer]] would be able to educate industrial mechanics, but not e.g., laboratory assistants or civil builders."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "20c6dc93-2b2d-45da-a530-c5853d8db60c",
      "text": "# After the apprenticeship of trade and craft professions"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "56fb087a-2d06-47c0-b52c-0699c656168a",
      "text": "When the apprenticeship is ended, the former apprentice now is considered a [[journeyman]]. He may choose to go on his [[journeyman years]]-travels."
    }
