      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "f1067d3c-607e-4ae8-881e-80452e88936a",
        "text": "After completion of the dual education, e.g., a baker is allowed to call himself a bakery [[journeyman]] (''Bäckergeselle''). After the apprenticeship the journeyman can enter the master's school (''Meisterschule'') and continue his education at evening courses for 3–4 years or full-time for about one year. The graduation from the master's school leads to the title of a [[master craftsman]] (''Meister'') of his profession, so e.g., a bakery master is entitled as ''Bäckermeister''. A master is officially entered in the local trade register, the craftspeople's roll (''Handwerksrolle''). A master craftsman is allowed to employ and to train new apprentices. In some mostly safety-related professions, e.g., that of [[electrician]]s only a master is allowed to found his own company."
